    <div id="text"> 
                 <p>
       <div id="intro">     <strong> Hi there! </strong> My name is Sandy Lin, I'm a freelance illustrator, designer, and tattoo artist based in Toronto, Ontario. I work with a multitude of clients but mainly in tattoo designs, advertising, and illustration. I believe in visual story-telling, how creativity communicates through you. 
        </div>
                
           <h1><a name="One"style="font-weight: 40" >My Story</a></h1>
 <div id="mystory">      <p> So how did I start? 
        My love for tattoos has always been an ever present characteristic since I was a child, and as time went on, it only flourished.
        In school, I was quite shy, and kept to myself, instead of listening to my teachers, I opted to spend my time drawing. And this habit soon became long sessions decorating my skin with intricate designs using ballpoint pens, eyeliner, and sealing it with hairspray.
    
     <br> </br>
     My "mock" tattoo sleeves started to gain traction among my friends, and the next thing I knew, I would spend at least one hour of my time in the school day <i>tattooing</i> someone.</p>  </div>
<br> </br>
      

        <br>
<div id="mystorypt2" >
            <p>
    However, it was the look of pure happiness and awe of their reactions when I finished drawing on them that helped me from my romance with body art. Ever since then, it's been one of my biggest goals to become a tattoo artist, and over the course of 2019, through online courses and experimentation, I taught myself the art of tattooing. 
                <br> </br>
                Don't get me wrong though, I'm still learning, and I know that I still have a long way to go before I reach the level of artistry I aspire to be at.</p>
  <p>
Currently, I work mainly in black and grey, with splashes of red and blue, in my own version of asian traditional style, and mainly in black and grey with small pops of colour.
          
          
         At the moment, I'm studying Global Business and Digital Arts at the University of Waterloo, however, I'm also open to tattoo apprenticeship opportunities. 
</p>
            
